{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17000"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17000"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.29,0.33,0.06,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68187"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9690"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53644"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"9618"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22821"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68187"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newborn boy is referred to the Emergency Department from a regional hospital with concerns about his anus. He was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery. He has not passed meconium at 24 hours of age. He has no other medical history and takes no medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is slightly distended but soft. There is no anal opening visible, but there is a small dimple at the expected location. A small amount of meconium is noted at the tip of his penis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home with follow-up","Magnetic resonance imaging","Immediate colostomy formation","Digital rectal examination","Cross-table lateral X-ray"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis newborn presents with features of an anorectal malformation with rectourethral fistula, as evidenced by the absence of an anal opening and meconium at the penile tip. The management approach depends on accurate determination of the type of malformation and the presence of associated anomalies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECross-table lateral X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E after 24 hours of life is the initial investigation of choice. This helps determine the level of the rectal pouch in relation to the perineum, which guides surgical management. The presence of air within 1 cm of the perineum suggests a low lesion that may be amenable to primary repair.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate colostomy formation\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary but should not be performed before appropriate imaging has been completed and the type of malformation has been determined. Some low lesions may be amenable to primary repair without the need for initial colostomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful later for surgical planning but is not the appropriate first investigation in the acute setting. It requires general anaesthesia in a newborn and does not provide the immediate information needed for initial management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigital rectal examination\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in a suspected anorectal malformation as it may create a false passage and complicate surgical repair.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home with follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this condition requires urgent evaluation and management to prevent complications such as bowel obstruction and sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAssociated anomalies are common in anorectal malformations (occurring in up to 60% of cases), particularly those affecting the genitourinary system, spine, and cardiovascular system. Therefore, a thorough physical examination and appropriate screening investigations should be performed. The VACTERL association (Vertebral defects, Anal atresia, Cardiac defects, Tracheo-Esophageal fistula, Renal anomalies, and Limb abnormalities) should be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anorectal malformations should be suspected in any newborn with an imperforate anus or abnormal anal position.","The presence or absence of a fistula and its location determines the classification and surgical approach.","Initial management includes nasogastric decompression and cross-table lateral X-ray to determine presence of air in the perineum."],"references":["Bhatnagar S. Anorectal malformations (part 2). J Neonatal Surg. 2015 Apr 1;4(2):25. PMID: 26034719; PMCID: PMC4447478."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53644"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17000"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53644"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:30:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:31:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9690"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68187"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji"